                  <formatted-text>
                    <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Arial' fontsize='11'>Before diving into the urban-rural differences, it’s important to understand why lifestyle matters. There is strong evidence that lifestyle habits affect sleep and overall wellbeing. Studies in Bhutan and other populations show that sleep is closely linked to health. For example, research based on Bhutan’s Gross National Happiness survey found that people who sleep too little (6 hours or less) or too much (11 hours or more) are more likely to report poor health. This suggests that both insufficient and excessive sleep can negatively affect wellbeing (Sithey et al., 2017).</run>
                    <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
                    <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Arial' fontsize='11'>Sleep quality is also an important factor in mental health. A study among people with epilepsy in Bhutan found that individuals with poor sleep were more likely to experience depression and social isolation. This indicates that disturbed sleep affects not only physical health but also emotional and psychological wellbeing (Stauder et al., 2020). Similar findings are seen among older adults, where sleep problems such as insomnia are associated with lower quality of life, especially when combined with other conditions like pain and depression (Dorji et al., 2018).</run>
                    <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
                    <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Arial' fontsize='11'>Work and daily routines further influence sleep and wellbeing. Research on nurses in Bhutan shows that those who are able to rest properly, such as by taking naps during night shifts, experience less fatigue and perform better at work (Gyeltshen et al., 2023). In contrast, studies on workers in Thimphu indicate that high workload and job stress are common and can negatively impact mental wellbeing (Naveed et al., 2020).</run>
                    <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
                    <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Arial' fontsize='11'>In addition, modern lifestyle habits such as screen use are increasingly affecting sleep. Studies among young adults show that spending long hours on smartphones, especially before bedtime, is linked to poor sleep quality and increased daytime tiredness. Higher screen use is consistently associated with more sleep disturbances and lower energy levels (Deivendran et al., 2025).</run>
